column859: I was not impressed that the scenario was identical, save for the risk map, in each round.  Every round was "single-story motel in City XX in the southeastern U.S. As you are checking your phone, your weather forecast application (app) warns that there is a line of thunderstorms moving southwest to northeast and may produce tornadoes with wind speeds of between 86-135 miles per hour. This wind speed may cause moderate to considerable damage according to the Enhanced Fujita Scale of tornadoes."  I would have preferred to see a bit more variation - in fact, the risk maps seemed to suggest that all storms were moving at a 45deg angle from SE to NW.  However, at least here in Louisiana, they're often moving NE to SW, and at a range of angles.  I've seen storm fronts moving anywhere from around 10deg to almost 170deg.  Some idea of the speed of the storm front generating the tornadoes would have been nice, as well.  Perhaps I missed it in the instructions, but I wasn't certain whether I was being asked if I would get hit by a tornado from that storm cell at all, or simply if I was going to get hit before the next warning.  The addition of the phrase "in the next ten minutes" might have clarified that.
